\subsection{Loess Fit}

To improve upon the previous algorithm, the first step must be to eliminate the grooves from the images under the assumption that they do not contain relevant information for determining a match. Fortunately, the location and appearance of the grooves in these 2d plots is quite consistent. By noting that height values beginning at $y = 0$ reach a maximum around the peak of the groove, we can then follow the descent of the height values to valley of the groove. This marks the point at which we should trim the image. We repeat a similar procedure for the right-hand groove by starting at the maximum y value and working backwards. The procedure can be described as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Fix an $x$ coordinate value (Figure~\ref{fig:loess_step12}).
    \item For each y value, compute a rolling average to smooth out any deviations occurring near the minima. (Figure~\ref{fig:loess_step12}).
    \item Determine the peak of the left groove by finding the first value with a negative discretized derivative. Determine the valley of the left groove by finding the first value with a positive discretized derivative after the value of the peak. (Figure~\ref{fig:loess_step34}).
    \item Determine the peak of the right groove by finding the last value with a positive discretized derivative. Determine the valley of the right groove by finding the last value with a negative discretized derivative before the value of the peak. (Figure~\ref{fig:loess_step34}).
    \item Remove all $y$ values left and right of the identified minima in vertical direction (Figure \ref{fig:loess_step34}).
\end{enumerate}

Next, we fit a Loess regression to the data. Figure \ref{fig:loess_fit} provides a look at the Loess fit, in blue, overlaid against the processed image of part 1 of bullet 1. The fit seems to do a reasonable job of capturing the structure of the image. Figure \ref{fig:loess_resid} shows the residuals from this fit. It is clear that there is a rather significant amount of autocorrelation, which make sense given the presence of striations and markings. Certainly, tuning the parameters for this regression, such as the Loess span, could prove to do an even better job at making the markings more clear. \hh{XXX did you follow up on that? What is the effect of using a different span?}

